        {
            "id": "intro_loop_control",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Loop Control",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Sometimes you need to control how a loop runs. You might want to stop the loop early or skip some iterations. Python provides `break` and `continue` for this."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`break` stops the loop completely. `continue` skips the rest of the current iteration and goes to the next one."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "break_statement",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The `break` Statement",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `break` statement immediately stops the loop and continues with the code after the loop."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "for i in range(5):\n    print(f\"Number: {i}\")\n    break\n\nprint(\"Loop finished!\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Number: 0\nLoop finished!"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The loop stops on the first iteration, because of the `break` statement, even though `range(5)` would normally go from 0 to 4."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "continue_statement",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The `continue` Statement",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `continue` statement skips the rest of the current iteration and goes to the next one."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "for i in range(5):\n    if i == 2:\n        continue\n    print(f\"Number: {i}\")\n\nprint(\"Loop finished!\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Number: 0\nNumber: 1\nNumber: 3\nNumber: 4\nLoop finished!"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When `i` equals `2`, `continue` skips the `print` statement and goes to the next iteration, so `2` is not printed."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "break_with_while",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can use `break` and `continue` with `while` loops too. `break` is useful when you want to stop the loop based on a condition inside the `while` loop. `continue` is useful when you want to skip the rest of the current iteration and go to the next one."
                }
            ]
        },
